# implement-intake-format

## Rule
A ticket authored by `/author-ticket` and a ticket consumed by `/implement` share **one schema**, so anything authored is implementable without rework. A ticket is in-format when its description contains:

1. **Problem statement / user story** — what + why.
2. **Acceptance criteria** — at least one, testable. (`/bugfix`: also **reproduction steps**.)
3. **Routing block** — building block, affected repo(s), suggested component, blast radius (shared-service consumers).

Canonical object (a single leaf issue):
```json
{
  "title": "...",
  "type": "Story|Task|Bug",                  // parent type is AI-classified; a leaf may be any of these
  "problem_statement": "...",
  "acceptance_criteria": ["..."],
  "reproduction_steps": ["..."],            // bug only
  "building_block": "My Rates Management",
  "affected_repos": ["fb-rates-go"],
  "component": "My Rates Management",        // JIRA component the board filters on
  "blast_radius": ["EFP","ATLAS"]           // products affected if a shared service changes
}
```

## Hierarchical (tree) shape — `/author-ticket`
`/author-ticket` may author a **tree**: one parent issue (`Story|Task|Bug`, AI-classified) plus zero or more
**sub-tasks** the user listed. Each sub-task is a leaf and MUST satisfy the leaf schema above so it is
`/implement`-ready on its own. The parent is a **container**: it carries the problem/story and links the leaves;
`/implement` runs on **leaves**, never on a parent that has sub-tasks (see [`ticket-completeness`](ticket-completeness.md)).

```json
{
  "parent": {
    "title": "...",
    "type": "Story|Task|Bug",               // AI-proposed from the idea, user-confirmed at Gate-P
    "problem_statement": "...",
    "acceptance_criteria": ["..."],          // parent-level, may be a rollup of the sub-tasks
    "building_block": "...",
    "component": "...",
    "epic": "EFP-900" | null                 // existing epic to link (never auto-picked); null = no link
  },
  "sub_tasks": [                             // user-listed only; AI enriches, never invents (unknowns → TBD)
    {
      "title": "...", "type": "Sub-task",    // sub-tasks are ALWAYS issuetype Sub-task
      "problem_statement": "...", "acceptance_criteria": ["..."],
      "reproduction_steps": ["..."],         // if the sub-task is a bug
      "building_block": "...", "affected_repos": ["..."], "component": "...", "blast_radius": ["..."]
    }
  ]
}
```
A flat single-issue authoring is just this tree with `sub_tasks: []` — the parent then *is* the leaf and is
`/implement`-ready directly.

## Fields are createmeta-driven (read live, never hardcode)
Which fields exist on an issue, which are **required**, and their allowed values are read at author-time from JIRA
**createmeta** for the resolved `project + issuetype` — never hardcoded. The AI fills what it can ground
(summary, description = problem + AC + repro, component = building block, issue type, parent, labels); the user
sets the rest at Gate-P or via flags (assignee, priority, sprint, fix version, story points, team custom fields).
**Required-field guard:** every field createmeta marks `required` must be satisfied before create — fill it from its
default (e.g. fb-tech's custom **Issue Source** defaults to `User Generated`), else prompt the user, so create never
fails on a missing required field. `type` values (`Story|Task|Bug|Sub-task`) come live from the project's createmeta,
not from this doc.

## Why
`/implement`'s `ticket-completeness` gate refuses under-specified tickets. Authoring against the same schema means the producer (`ticket-composer-agent`) and the consumer (`jira-agent` → `jira-ticket-parser`) never disagree on shape — the authored ticket passes the developer's gate by construction.

## Constraints
- The producer fills every field from the brains or marks it `TBD — <question>`; it never fabricates acceptance criteria (`no-invented-facts`).
- **Sub-tasks are user-listed, never AI-invented.** The AI enriches (routes + drafts problem/AC for) each sub-task the user provides; it never adds sub-tasks the user didn't ask for. Unknowns inside a sub-task become `TBD — <question>` (`no-invented-facts`). Optional `suggest` mode may *propose* a breakdown for the user to accept/edit at Gate-P, but the tree is never created without the user's confirmation.
- Each sub-task in `sub_tasks[]` MUST independently satisfy the leaf schema (problem + ≥1 AC, + repro if it's a bug) — that is what makes it `/implement`-ready.
- `building_block` / `affected_repos` come from `routing.json`; `blast_radius` from `consumer-registry.json`.
- `component` maps to a real JIRA component via `jira-integration/jira-projects.json`; if unknown → blank + Triage.
- The parent's `epic` is an **existing** epic to link, resolved from `--epic`, an inline mention, or a Gate-P shortlist — **never auto-picked**; `null` means no link. A new epic is created only with `--create-epic` (see [`jira-write-permissions`](jira-write-permissions.md)).
- The consumer (`jira-ticket-parser`) reads the same fields back out — field names here are authoritative for both lanes.

## Examples
### Good
> Title: "Show FRLC charges on the rate card." Problem: shippers can't see FRLC line items. AC: rate card lists each FRLC charge with amount; total reconciles. Building block: My Rates Management. Repos: fb-rates-go. Component: My Rates Management. Blast radius: EFP, ATLAS.

### Bad
> "FRLC stuff" — no problem statement, no AC, no routing.

